From @realmoney @jimcramer @tomkeene The Amazon Divorce This week I sold Amazon ($AMZN) - after the shares rose by nearly $300 since my purchase in late December. (The stock remains on my Best Ideas List.)

Yesterday it was announced that Jeff Bezos and his wife are getting divorced. While Apple ($AAPL) survived and has prospered under Tim Cook... is it premature to ask what happens to Amazon when Jeff Bezos chooses to turn over the day to day running of the company he founded?
His announced divorce gives me pause for thought. I suspect that if the stock dips on this news it may be a buy but longer term it is a real question mark in my opinion. @cnbcfastmoney @SquawkCNBC

Rev, I dont believe you answered my question. How can you trust a trend made up of moves by machines and algos?
What was our $M bet Sarge?

In other words, if machines and algos temporarily create an artificiality in prices, how can you rely and react to that price pattern, especially if it is likely to shortly mean reverse? Arent the charts screwed up by machines and algos, so we have to be less dependent

You write: "The best way to deal with this tendency of the market to go from one extreme to the other is to be less anticipatory and more reactive. Trying to guess when a trend will turn is fraught with peril." If algos/machines exaggerate moves, how do you trust that trend?

And why wouldnt you do just the opposite and anticipate a "normalization" or return back to price discovery - buying exaggerated machine selling and selling exaggerated machine buying? I have incorporated this anticipation in my trading. Thanks, Rev.

@realmoney Full disclosure, full transparency... Jan 09, 2019 | 04:42 PM EST DOUG KASS It's the Business I Have Chosen I was a large buyer of stocks during the last half of December. On the market's extraordinary strength since Christmas I have made a number of portfolio

changes this week: * Eliminated longs in 3M (MMM) , Amazon (AMZN) and Google (GOOGL) . * Reduced long holdings in Square (SQ) , CBS (CBS) * Initiated longs in (MJ) and (CGC) * Established a Spyder short (progressively as the market rose and more meaningfully over the last two

days) I have moved from a large net long exposure to a short exposure. I have been an active and anticipatory trader over the last few months (while maintaining long-term investment positions) and I dont see anything that will change my strategy of dealing with the regime of

volatility that began a year ago. I have not and don't plan to be reactive in my trading - because in a trading market (with a broad range) there does not appear to be a primary trend to capitalize on, just opportunities to trade against machines, algos and extreme moves in

investor sentiment. This approach is not for everyone - nor does it mean more patient strategies will not be rewarding. But this approach is serving me well (so I will continue to throw the dice), is consistent with my risk appetite and is the business I have chosen .

(Which means I am about to implode!) I anticipate the trading range, as most are aware, will ultimately be broken to the downside in response to a sharp deceleration in the rate of global growth and a meaingful miss to corporate profits.
